# C++ Coding Standards

## Language Standards
- Use **C++17/20** features
- Prefer modern C++ idioms over legacy patterns
- Use RAII principles for resource management
- Follow exception safety guarantees

## Best Practices

### Memory Management
- Prefer smart pointers (`std::unique_ptr`, `std::shared_ptr`) over raw pointers
- Use RAII for resource management
- Avoid memory leaks and dangling pointers

### Modern C++ Features
- Use structured bindings when appropriate
- Prefer `auto` for type deduction (when it improves readability)
- Use range-based for loops
- Use `constexpr` and `const` appropriately

### Error Handling
- Use exceptions for exceptional circumstances
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Follow exception safety guarantees

### Performance
- Consider cache-friendly data layouts
- Avoid false sharing (arrange data to minimize multiple threads modifying variables on the same cache line)
- Use move semantics to avoid unnecessary copies
- Profile code before optimizing

## Architecture Compatibility
- Ensure code works on both **x64** (primary) and **x86** (secondary) architectures
- Use proper type sizes (consider `int32_t`, `int64_t` instead of `int`, `long`)
- Be aware of pointer size differences between architectures
